04823nam a22006615i 9780801467097DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20132013nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808014670977 a10.7591/97808014670972doi  a(DE-B1597)535878  a(OCoLC)1121052514  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aHIS0140002bisacsh04a355.02130943090341 aHull, Isabel V., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAbsolute Destruction :bMilitary Culture and the Practices of War in Imperial Germany /cIsabel V. Hull. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (400 p.) :b5 maps, 1 table, 16 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tMaps -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tPART I. Suppression Becomes Annihilation: Southwest Africa, 1904–1907 -- tPART II. Military Culture -- tPART III. The First World War -- tConclusions and Implications -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn a book that is at once a major contribution to modern European history and a cautionary tale for today, Isabel V. Hull argues that the routines and practices of the Imperial German Army, unchecked by effective civilian institutions, increasingly sought the absolute destruction of its enemies as the only guarantee of the nation's security. So deeply embedded were the assumptions and procedures of this distinctively German military culture that the Army, in its drive to annihilate the enemy military, did not shrink from the utter destruction of civilian property and lives. Carried to its extreme, the logic of "military necessity" found real security only in extremities of destruction, in the "silence of the graveyard."Hull begins with a dramatic account, based on fresh archival work, of the German Army's slide from administrative murder to genocide in German Southwest Africa (1904–7). The author then moves back to 1870 and the war that inaugurated the Imperial era in German history, and analyzes the genesis and nature of this specifically German military culture and its operations in colonial warfare. In the First World War the routines perfected in the colonies were visited upon European populations. Hull focuses on one set of cases (Belgium and northern France) in which the transition to total destruction was checked (if barely) and on another (Armenia) in which "military necessity" caused Germany to accept its ally's genocidal policies even after these became militarily counterproductive. She then turns to the Endkampf (1918), the German General Staff's plan to achieve victory in the Great War even if the homeland were destroyed in the process—a seemingly insane campaign that completes the logic of this deeply institutionalized set of military routines and practices. Hull concludes by speculating on the role of this distinctive military culture in National Socialism's military and racial policies.Absolute Destruction has serious implications for the nature of warmaking in any modern power. At its heart is a warning about the blindness of bureaucratic routines, especially when those bureaucracies command the instruments of mass death.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 4aEurope. 4aHistory. 4aMilitary History. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Germany.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080146709740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801467097423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780801467097.jpg  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKA